Today we’re talking IV’s ✨ Did you know the lower the number of the gauge of the needle means the needle is bigger? 

The higher the number, the smaller the needle, kind of confusing right? I honestly love using a 22g since most of my patients have small veins or very difficult to access veins. I feel like I can get a 22g into anyone. Don’t get me wrong, I do love an 18g, but not everyone has beautiful veins. Most of my patients either get a 20g or a 22g. They’d get an 18g or a 16g if they really needed it (for a blood transfusion, rapid fluid administration, medications, etc). I have put many 16Gs in my life but most of those were when I worked as a paramedic taking care of trauma patients.

Needles are identified by color. 
Yellow-24G
Blue-22G
Pink-20G
Green-18G
Grey-16G

⭐️Nurse to patient. Face Shingles to Ramsay Hunt Syndrome. It has been a whole month of having right-side paralysis. Saying it’s been challenging is an understatement. My right eye cannot close, and my smile is lopsided, making me self-conscious. I drink with a straw, and eating is frustrating as I would bite my tongue and the right side of my cheek, and I drool. But I think I have always drooled🤦🏽‍♀️. It has impaired my right side hearing, taste buds, dryness to my right eye, and inability to show emotion. As frustrated as I am, I am learning to stand still (which is hard for me) and using this experience to help me with my paralysis patients. My family has been my rock. My husband has the patience of a saint. As much as I get frustrated repeating myself, I can’t imagine what my kids and husband are going through. Grateful for an amazing family and friends 💛 #nurse #paralysisrecovery #facialparalysis #ramsay #bellspalsy #bellspalsyawareness #bellspalsyrecovery #bellspalsyawareness #ramsayhuntsyndrome .

At work, I’m always singing, dancing, laughing, and sometimes I am frustrated, but I get over it quickly…sometimes 😉I love talking to my patients, and at times, I need to give them hard love. Bells Palsey vs. Ramsay Hunt Syndrome. With Bells Palsey, most people fully recover within a few weeks, with or without treatment. There is not one-fits-all-treatment. Your health care may suggest medications and PT. Surgery is rare. Ramsay Hunt usually has the worst prognosis than Bells Palsey. Usually, good prognosis if you have treatment within 3 days. Untreated, the prognosis for Ramsay Hunt is much won't than Bells Palsey with well over 50% permanent paralysis or weakness. .
